{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477045"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:56:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:56:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14163"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.37,0.05,0.15,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1156"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2462"},{"type":"tags","id":"2519"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46081"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy is referred to the Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery clinic with a three-month history of persistent left jaw pain and swelling. He also reports occasional fever and fatigue. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a firm, tender swelling over the left mandible. His dentition appears normal. Skin examination reveals a scaly, erythematous rash on his scalp. A panoramic radiograph reveals a 2 cm lytic lesion in the left mandibular ramus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incisional biopsy","Fine needle aspiration","Dental extraction","Oral antibiotics","Watchful waiting"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELangerhans cell histiocytosis (LCH) is a rare disorder characterised by the proliferation of abnormal Langerhans cells. It can affect various organs, but bone involvement is common, particularly in the skull and jaw. The condition can present with solitary or multiple lytic bone lesions, and may be associated with systemic symptoms such as fever and fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. This procedure is necessary to obtain a definitive diagnosis of LCH. The biopsy specimen should undergo histopathological examination and immunohistochemical staining for CD1a and CD207 (langerin), which are characteristic markers of Langerhans cells. A definitive diagnosis is crucial for appropriate treatment planning and prognosis assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E may not provide sufficient tissue for a definitive diagnosis of LCH. An incisional biopsy is preferred as it allows for better tissue sampling and architectural preservation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDental extraction\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The panoramic radiograph shows normal dentition, and the lytic lesion is in the mandibular ramus rather than associated with a specific tooth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the first step in this case. While dental infections can cause jaw swelling, the prolonged duration of symptoms, the presence of a lytic lesion on imaging, and the additional systemic symptoms make an infectious aetiology less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate given the persistent symptoms, the presence of a lytic lesion, and the additional systemic symptoms. This approach could delay diagnosis and treatment of a potentially serious condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the differential diagnosis, other conditions to consider include osteomyelitis, benign bone tumours (such as giant cell tumour or aneurysmal bone cyst), and malignant bone tumours (such as Ewing sarcoma or osteosarcoma). However, the clinical presentation with the combination of a lytic jaw lesion, scalp rash, and systemic symptoms is most consistent with LCH. After confirming the diagnosis, further evaluation for multisystem involvement and appropriate treatment, which may include chemotherapy, radiation, or surgery, would be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Langerhans cell histiocytosis can present with lytic bone lesions, particularly in the skull and jaw.","Langerhans cell histiocytosis should be considered in the differential diagnosis of persistent bone pain or swelling in children.","Biopsy with immunohistochemical staining for CD1a and CD207 is necessary for definitive diagnosis of Langerhans cell histiocytosis."],"references":["Allen CE, Merad M, McClain KL. Langerhans-Cell Histiocytosis. N Engl J Med. 2018 Aug 30;379(9):856-868. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30157397/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14163"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T21:04:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-31T07:59:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1061"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Fever","synonyms":["Pyrexia","Febrile","High temperature","Elevated temperature","Increased temperature","Fevers","Low-grade fever"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-06-11T11:13:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T13:18:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1063"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Rash","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-06-11T11:19:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T16:03:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1156"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Jaw pain","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-28T10:33:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T16:20:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2436"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Fatigue","synonyms":["Tiredness","Lethargy","Daytime sleepiness"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-07-03T10:14:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T16:34:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2462"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"X-ray - jaw","synonyms":["x-ray - mandible"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-07-05T16:18:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-05T16:18:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"4"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2519","links":{"self"